<DOC><DOCNO> AP890116-0025 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-16-89 0128EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     01-16 0436</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,400</SECOND><HEAD>Percentage Of Black Males In Colleges Declines</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Minority enrollment in U.S. colleges increasedover the past decade, but the number of black males enrolleddeclined.   Black males also earned the fewest degrees and made the leastprogress in number of faculty positions held, the American Councilon Education said Sunday in its seventh annual status report onMinorities in Higher Education.   Federal statistics reviewed by the council found total collegeenrollment grew from 11 million to 12.5 million from 1976 to 1986,but black male enrollment fell from 470,000 to 436,000. Black women,by contrast, held a steady share throughout the period, starting at5.1 percent and ending at 5.2 percent.   Asian and Hispanic participation jumped 15 percent and 17 percentrespectively from 1984 to 1986, fueling an 8 percent gain forminorities as a group, said the report.</TEXT><NOTE>___</NOTE><NOTE>Senate Banking Chief Says Plenty Of Blame For Everyone In Sandamp;L Flap</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The chairman of the Senate Banking Committeesays there likely will have to be changes made in the savings andloan industry because of the crisis that could cost taxpayers morethan $100 billion.   Sen. Donald Riegle, D-Mich., whose committee will have to dealwith the issue, was not specific Sunday about what changes he has inmind.   Riegle, appearing on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' said that whileSandamp;Ls must put their focus on providing home mortgages, it would be``an enormous shift backwards' to require them to limit theiractivities to such mortgages.   Riegle said the Sandamp;L industry's problems are ``a sharedresponsibility'' and he blamed not only the industry and itsregulators, but also President Reagan and Congress. ``The regulatoryprocess broke down,'' he said.</TEXT><NOTE>___</NOTE><NOTE>Defense Chief Says Pentagon Cuts Could Be Devastating</NOTE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Outgoing Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci iswarning that automatic cuts in the Pentagon budget mandated underthe Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction law would be ``devastating.''   There has been speculation that if the Bush administration andCongress fail to reach agreement on reducing the federal budgetdeficit, the White House might be willing to accept the automaticspending cuts.   ``It would certainly be devastating to the Defense Department.... Based on preliminary estimates we'd have to take something like$26 billion out of the Defense Department,'' Carlucci said Sunday onABC's ``This Week With David Brinkley.''   ``Our force structure is down to about the minimum you can getand still maintain our rotation schedules,'' he said. ``So cuts ofthose dimensions would really mean laying up ships, getting rid ofpeople, taking away ammunition.''</TEXT></DOC>